  ('westin-poinsett-hotel', 'Westin Poinsett Hotel', 'Greenville', '120 South Main Street', 'SC', 34.8510, -82.4001, 'hotel',
   'A grand 1925 hotel in downtown Greenville where guests report unexplained knocks in empty hallways and encounters with the ghost of an elderly man who appears in their rooms.',
   'The Westin Poinsett Hotel opened in 1925 as one of the finest hotels in the upstate, a 12-story landmark in the heart of downtown Greenville. Named for Joel Poinsett, the South Carolina statesman who introduced the poinsettia to America, the hotel has hosted countless guests over its century of operation. Guests report hearing knocks and noises in empty hallways, particularly on the upper floors late at night. Multiple guests have reported waking to find the apparition of an elderly man standing in their room, watching them before fading away. The identity of the ghost is unknown, though some speculate it may be a former long-term resident who died in the hotel. Staff have reported elevators stopping at floors where no one called them, and housekeeping has found rooms disturbed after being cleaned when no guests had access.',
   1925, 'https://kiddingaroundgreenville.com/haunted-places-in-the-upstate',
   '["https://kiddingaroundgreenville.com/haunted-places-in-the-upstate","https://sctravelguide.com/2018/06/11/haunted-places-in-upstate-sc/"]', 2),

  ('springwood-cemetery', 'Springwood Cemetery', 'Greenville', '1000 East Washington Street', 'SC', 34.8517, -82.3847, 'cemetery',
   'A historic downtown Greenville cemetery haunted by Fannie Heldmann, who drowned herself in the Reedy River in 1889 to escape an arranged marriage.',
   'Springwood Cemetery is the oldest and largest public cemetery in Greenville, established in the 1820s and containing the remains of many of the city''s most prominent citizens. The cemetery''s most famous ghost is Fannie Heldmann, whose father insisted she marry his business partner. Fannie was repulsed by the arrangement and reportedly went insane planning the unwanted wedding. In 1889, she drowned herself in the Reedy River rather than go through with the marriage. Her spirit is said to haunt both the cemetery where she is buried and the banks of the Reedy River nearby. Visitors have reported seeing a young woman in Victorian-era clothing walking among the older graves at twilight, and some have heard crying near her headstone. The cemetery is also known for unexplained cold spots and the feeling of being followed along its winding paths.',
   1829, 'https://livingupstatesc.com/the-spooky-and-supernatural-of-upstate-south-carolina/',
   '["https://livingupstatesc.com/the-spooky-and-supernatural-of-upstate-south-carolina/","https://gvltoday.6amcity.com/scary-stories-greenville-sc"]', 2),

  ('greenville-tb-hospital', 'Greenville Tuberculosis Hospital', 'Greenville', '400 Herdklotz Park Drive', 'SC', 34.8683, -82.3739, 'hospital',
   'The ruins of a former tuberculosis hospital and asylum in Greenville, where shadow figures still wander the grounds and screams echo from the destroyed building.',
   'The Greenville Tuberculosis Hospital began treating TB patients in the early 1900s but later also served as an insane asylum and prisoner release facility. The combination of suffering, death, and institutionalization left a dark mark on the property. Though the main hospital building burned down years ago, the grounds — now Herdklotz Park — remain one of the most investigated paranormal sites in upstate South Carolina. Strange sounds including banging, screaming, and the clanging of bells have been heard and even recorded by paranormal teams. Shadow figures are seen wandering the park area, particularly near where the hospital once stood. Visitors report an overwhelming sense of dread near the old building foundations, and electronic equipment frequently malfunctions on the grounds.',
   1910, 'https://kiddingaroundgreenville.com/haunted-places-in-the-upstate',
   '["https://kiddingaroundgreenville.com/haunted-places-in-the-upstate","https://sctravelguide.com/2018/06/11/haunted-places-in-upstate-sc/"]', 2),

  ('oakwood-cemetery-spartanburg', 'Oakwood Cemetery', 'Spartanburg', '800 North Church Street', 'SC', 34.9567, -81.9283, 'cemetery',
   'Known locally as Hell''s Gate, this Spartanburg cemetery is haunted by the Lady in White — a young bride who died on her wedding day and was buried in her wedding dress.',
   'Oakwood Cemetery in Spartanburg, considered one of the most actively haunted places in South Carolina, has earned the nickname Hell''s Gate among locals. The cemetery''s most famous spirit is the Lady in White — a young woman who died on her wedding day and was buried in her wedding dress. Her ghostly figure has been seen walking among the graves in a flowing white gown, particularly on moonlit nights. Paranormal investigators report an unusually high concentration of activity: cold spots appear without explanation, camera and phone batteries drain rapidly, and children''s laughter echoes from sections where young ones are buried. Visitors have photographed plumes of unexplained smoke and fog, and many report the intense feeling of being watched. A young boy''s voice has been heard asking to be played with near the children''s section.',
   1870, 'https://www.southcarolinahauntedhouses.com/real-haunts/',
   '["https://www.southcarolinahauntedhouses.com/real-haunts/","https://livingupstatesc.com/the-spooky-and-supernatural-of-upstate-south-carolina/","https://sctravelguide.com/2018/06/11/haunted-places-in-upstate-sc/"]', 3),

  ('fosters-tavern-spartanburg', 'Foster''s Tavern', 'Spartanburg', '295 East Main Street', 'SC', 34.9499, -81.9208, 'restaurant',
   'A historic Spartanburg landmark where phantom footsteps echo from empty staircases and the sound of ghostly horses pound on the roof.',
   'Foster''s Tavern is one of Spartanburg''s oldest and most historic landmarks, serving the community since the early days of the city. The tavern has long been known for its paranormal activity, which staff and patrons have reported for generations. Footsteps are heard on empty staircases throughout the building, particularly after closing time. Most bizarrely, the sound of horses galloping across the roof has been reported by multiple witnesses — a phenomenon that has never been explained. Some speculate the horse sounds are connected to the building''s history as a coach stop, where horses and riders were a constant presence. Doors open and close without explanation, and staff have reported feeling cold breath on their necks while working alone in the kitchen. The building''s age and connection to colonial-era travel routes contribute to its haunted reputation.',
   1807, 'https://livingupstatesc.com/the-spooky-and-supernatural-of-upstate-south-carolina/',
   '["https://livingupstatesc.com/the-spooky-and-supernatural-of-upstate-south-carolina/","https://www.southcarolinahauntedhouses.com/real-haunts/"]', 2),

